(
<figureCitation id="33C42A6C6D63FB5BC698532D45A01055" box="[159,253,1281,1305]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 1–6" captionStart-1="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId-0="1.[151,264,1831,1855]" captionStartId-1="2.[151,264,1249,1273]" captionTargetBox-0="[151,1435,197,1806]" captionTargetBox-1="[166,1419,181,1219]" captionTargetId-0="figure-17@1.[151,1435,180,1806]" captionTargetId-1="figure-29@2.[157,1430,181,1225]" captionTargetPageId-0="1" captionTargetPageId-1="2" captionText-0="FIGURES 1–6. Ectopsocus disjunctus n. sp. Male: (1) Forewing. (2) Hindwing. (3) Front view of head. (4) Hypandrium. (5) Phallosome. (6) Clunium, paraprocts and epiproct. Scales in mm." captionText-1="FIGURES 7–9. Ectopsocus disjunctus n. sp. Female: (7) Ends of clunium, gonapophyses and ninth sternum. (8) Clunium, paraprocts and epiproct. (9) Subgenital plate. Scales in mm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541811" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541813" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6541811/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6541813/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="593">Figs 1–9</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E3E565626D63FB5BC6905309414C1289" pageId="0" pageNumber="593" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="AB4036E96D63FB5BC6905309414910BD" blockId="0.[151,1437,1245,1989]" pageId="0" pageNumber="593">
<emphasis id="998BEAFB6D63FB5BC690530944511071" bold="true" box="[151,268,1317,1341]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="593" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Belonging in species group 
<taxonomicName id="6CFF4D6A6D63FB5BC441530A47CA1071" authorityName="Thornton" authorityYear="1962" box="[582,663,1318,1341]" class="Insecta" family="Ectopsocidae" genus="Ectopsocus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Psocodea" pageId="0" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatus">
<emphasis id="998BEAFB6D63FB5BC441530A47CA1071" box="[582,663,1318,1341]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="593">ornatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of 
<bibRefCitation id="CF6E4B186D63FB5BC4B9530946841071" author="Thornton, I. W. B. &amp; Wong, S. K." box="[702,985,1317,1342]" pageId="0" pageNumber="593" pagination="1 - 158" refId="ref1728" refString="Thornton, I. W. B. &amp; Wong, S. K. (1968) The Peripsocid fauna (Psocoptera) of the Oriental region and the Pacific. Pacific Insects Monographs, 19, 1 - 158." type="journal article" year="1968">Thornton &amp; Wong (1968)</bibRefCitation>
. It is close to 
<taxonomicName id="6CFF4D6A6D63FB5BC272530A4583102D" authority="Garcia Aldrete (1991)" authorityName="Garcia Aldrete" authorityYear="1991" class="Insecta" family="Ectopsocidae" genus="Ectopsocus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Psocodea" pageId="0" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurus">
<emphasis id="998BEAFB6D63FB5BC272530A41A81071" box="[1141,1269,1317,1341]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="593">E. obscurus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="CF6E4B186D63FB5BC2F953094583102D" author="Garcia Aldrete, A. N." pageId="0" pageNumber="593" pagination="57 - 96" refId="ref1618" refString="Garcia Aldrete, A. N. (1991) The Mexican species of Ectopsocus (Psocoptera: Ectopsocidae) and an analysis of the distribution of the genus. Anales del Instituto de Biologia, Universidad Nacional Autonoma de Mexico, Serie Zoologia, 62 (1), 57 - 96." type="journal article" year="1991">García Aldrete (1991)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from the coast of 
<collectingRegion id="693BF80B6D63FB5BC7AC536544AB102D" box="[427,502,1353,1377]" country="Mexico" name="Jalisco" pageId="0" pageNumber="593">Jalisco</collectingRegion>
, with which species it shares a similar hypandrium, but differs in the phallosome and radular sclerites. The new species has a diagonal line of sclerotized papillae on each side of the clunium over the area of the epiproct and paraprocts, and one central, rounded hyaline area. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName id="6CFF4D6A6D63FB5BC20A53BE41D610E5" authorityName="Garcia Aldrete" authorityYear="1991" box="[1037,1163,1425,1449]" class="Insecta" family="Ectopsocidae" genus="Ectopsocus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Psocodea" pageId="0" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurus">
<emphasis id="998BEAFB6D63FB5BC20A53BE41D610E5" box="[1037,1163,1425,1449]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="593">E. obscurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a field of sclerotized papillae on each postero-lateral corner of the clunium, and lacks a central rounded hyaline area. The subgenital plates and gonapophyses of both species are similar, but the spermapore sclerites are different.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AB4036E96D63FB5BC6C053D145B01311" blockId="0.[151,1437,1245,1989]" pageId="0" pageNumber="593">
<emphasis id="998BEAFB6D63FB5BC6C053D1440C1359" bold="true" box="[199,337,1533,1557]" pageId="0" pageNumber="593">Male. Color</emphasis>
(in 80% ethanol). Body reddish brown. Compound eyes black, ocelli hyaline, with ochre centripetal crescents. Maxillary palps reddish brown. Antennae pale brown. Wings opaque, with a reddish brown hue. Abdomen pale reddish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AB4036E96D63FB5BC6C05045414C1289" blockId="0.[151,1437,1245,1989]" pageId="0" pageNumber="593">
<emphasis id="998BEAFB6D63FB5BC6C05045440713CD" bold="true" box="[199,346,1641,1665]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="593" reason="1">Morphology.</emphasis>
Hypandrium broad, almost rectangular, setose; posterior border with a setose lobe on each side of the longitudinal midline (
<figureCitation id="33C42A6C6D63FB5BC77A50A144E313E9" box="[381,446,1677,1701]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,197,1806]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[151,1435,180,1806]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Ectopsocus disjunctus n. sp. Male: (1) Forewing. (2) Hindwing. (3) Front view of head. (4) Hypandrium. (5) Phallosome. (6) Clunium, paraprocts and epiproct. Scales in mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541811" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6541811/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="593">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Phallosome (
<figureCitation id="33C42A6C6D63FB5BC45C50A147C613E9" box="[603,667,1677,1701]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,197,1806]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[151,1435,180,1806]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Ectopsocus disjunctus n. sp. Male: (1) Forewing. (2) Hindwing. (3) Front view of head. (4) Hypandrium. (5) Phallosome. (6) Clunium, paraprocts and epiproct. Scales in mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541811" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6541811/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="593">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
), with side struts short, stout, joined posteriorly with external parameres, these slightly curved, with apices bent outward. Internal parameres forming an arch, posteriorly wide, concave, with postero-lateral corners directed latero-posteriorly. Endophallus without sclerites, with two well defined, mesal, pigmented irregular bodies, and one posterior, arched, spinose body. Male clunium, over the area of the epiproct and paraprocts, posteriorly with a comb of 33-35 short, blunt ended, strongly sclerotized teeth; a rounded, hyaline area in the center, a line of sclerotized papillae on each side, from each postero-lateral corner toward the central hyaline area, or a field of sclerotized papillae on each postero-lateral corner as described in the diagnosis above (
<figureCitation id="33C42A6C6D63FB5BC5C75149415F1231" box="[960,1026,1893,1917]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,197,1806]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[151,1435,180,1806]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Ectopsocus disjunctus n. sp. Male: (1) Forewing. (2) Hindwing. (3) Front view of head. (4) Hypandrium. (5) Phallosome. (6) Clunium, paraprocts and epiproct. Scales in mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541811" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6541811/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="593">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Paraprocts (
<figureCitation id="33C42A6C6D63FB5BC292514941881231" box="[1173,1237,1893,1917]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,197,1806]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[151,1435,180,1806]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Ectopsocus disjunctus n. sp. Male: (1) Forewing. (2) Hindwing. (3) Front view of head. (4) Hypandrium. (5) Phallosome. (6) Clunium, paraprocts and epiproct. Scales in mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541811" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6541811/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="593">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) ovoid, with outer border sclerotized, bearing one cone and a row of setae, sensory fields with eight trichobothria issuing from basal rosettes, other setae as illustrated. Epiproct (
<figureCitation id="33C42A6C6D63FB5BC4175181470C1289" box="[528,593,1965,1989]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,197,1806]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[151,1435,180,1806]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Ectopsocus disjunctus n. sp. Male: (1) Forewing. (2) Hindwing. (3) Front view of head. (4) Hypandrium. (5) Phallosome. (6) Clunium, paraprocts and epiproct. Scales in mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541811" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6541811/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="593">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
), broadly bell-shaped, setae as illustrated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
