<paragraph id="AB4036E96D61FB59C6C0539641F113E5" blockId="2.[151,1437,1357,2029]" pageId="2" pageNumber="595">
<emphasis id="998BEAFB6D61FB59C6C053964407109E" bold="true" box="[199,346,1466,1490]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="595" reason="1">Morphology.</emphasis>
Subgenital plate (
<figureCitation id="33C42A6C6D61FB59C41E53954705109E" box="[537,600,1465,1490]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1249,1273]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,181,1219]" captionTargetId="figure-29@2.[157,1430,181,1225]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Ectopsocus disjunctus n. sp. Female: (7) Ends of clunium, gonapophyses and ninth sternum. (8) Clunium, paraprocts and epiproct. (9) Subgenital plate. Scales in mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541813" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6541813/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="595">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) broad, pigmented area widely concave anteriorly, 13-15 macrosetae on posterior transverse row, posterior processes stout, broadly triangular, each with four macrosetae apically. Gonapophyses (
<figureCitation id="33C42A6C6D61FB59C37653F145FA1356" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1249,1273]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,181,1219]" captionTargetId="figure-29@2.[157,1430,181,1225]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Ectopsocus disjunctus n. sp. Female: (7) Ends of clunium, gonapophyses and ninth sternum. (8) Clunium, paraprocts and epiproct. (9) Subgenital plate. Scales in mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541813" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6541813/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="595">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
): dorsal valves cylindrical, slightly curved, each bearing a row of six macrosetae on outer border. Spermapore sclerite broad, almost straight posteriorly, with a curved “handle” anteriorly. Paraprocts (
<figureCitation id="33C42A6C6D61FB59C5FB500941611372" box="[1020,1084,1573,1598]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1249,1273]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,181,1219]" captionTargetId="figure-29@2.[157,1430,181,1225]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Ectopsocus disjunctus n. sp. Female: (7) Ends of clunium, gonapophyses and ninth sternum. (8) Clunium, paraprocts and epiproct. (9) Subgenital plate. Scales in mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541813" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6541813/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="595">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) semi-elliptic, with half of outer border, next sensory fields, strongly sclerotized; a setal field distally, a transverse row of seven macrosetae, next each sensory field, these with eight trichobothria issuing from basal rosettes. Epiproct (
<figureCitation id="33C42A6C6D61FB59C2175041410D13CA" box="[1040,1104,1645,1670]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1249,1273]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,181,1219]" captionTargetId="figure-29@2.[157,1430,181,1225]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Ectopsocus disjunctus n. sp. Female: (7) Ends of clunium, gonapophyses and ninth sternum. (8) Clunium, paraprocts and epiproct. (9) Subgenital plate. Scales in mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6541813" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6541813/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="595">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) sinuous anteriorly, with sides converging to a rounded apex, a hyaline, transverse area next posterior border, setae as illustrated.
</paragraph>
